        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Primary sources, in case you didn�t know, are
        documents, photographs, videos, letters, and other materials that were
        made or produced at the time of the event by those directly
        involved.&nbsp; These sources should be unedited and in as raw a form as
        possible. <br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Civil War, for example, was the first war to have
        photography available to it.&nbsp; One of the most famous photographs
        was that of runaway slave Mr Oliver Gordon�s scarred back taken in
        1863.&nbsp; This primary source was physical proof to abolitionists and
        unionists of the brutality and moral bankruptcy of slavery.&nbsp; It
        inspired thousands of freed and enslaved African Americans to join the
        union army.&nbsp; (Matthew Brady Studio, 1863)</div>
      <img class="slaveback" src="https://npg.si.edu/sites/default/files/teacher_resources_gordon.jpg"

        alt="Oliver Gordons scarred back" title="Oliver Gordons scarred back">
      <div class="chapts">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Another primary source from the
        Civil War were the thousands and thousands of letters written by
        soldiers on either side of the war.&nbsp; These letters allow us to look
        at the everyday struggles and experiences of these soldiers whether they
        were at Gettysburg, Shiloh, Vicksburg, or the horrors of Georgia�s
        Andersonville prison.&nbsp; One such letter was written by Riley M
        Hoskinson of Illinois to his wife in which he describes his
        experiences.&nbsp; <br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sept. 17. Still all well here. Negley's Division gone
        before us towards the enemy. Gen. Thomas Army Corps are also gone in
        front of us and we (for the first time since in the service) left in the
        rear. Just at sunrise, boom goes a cannon, its fearful sound
        reverberating from mountain to mountain. Our men raise one long loud
        shout of joy. Soon several more followed in quick succession, then all
        silence for over an hour (Hoskinson, 1863). And, there are thousands of
        these letters that anyone can read in their original form or
        transcribed. <br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By contrast, secondary sources use primary sources to
        create a new document of what happened by editing primary sources
        together to create a narrative or story about the events that
        happened.&nbsp; <br>
        Secondary sources for the Civil War are just as abundant.&nbsp; A simple
        search at Amazon.com books reveals over 100,000 entries.&nbsp; However,
        the most famous secondary source of the Civil War is Ken Burn�s The
        Civil War documentary.&nbsp; At the time it aired, it was falsely
        believed that Americans didn�t have the attention span to watch a 12
        hour documentary (Burns, 1990); however, it ended up being the most
        watched series on PBS ever with 13.9 million viewers on its first
        night.&nbsp; (Carter, 1990).&nbsp; It featured the thousands of
        photographs taken during the war and the letters of soldiers sent
        home.&nbsp; <br>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As you can see, primary and secondary sources are
        very different.&nbsp; Primary sources are raw and unedited but also
        disconnected from each other and the larger picture; whereby, secondary
        sources are more connected but lack the pureness of a primary
        source.&nbsp; <br>
